He barely lived to reach Italy, and died at Brundisium September 22, ac. 19, aged not quite 51. Unwilling to leave the AEneid in its unfinished state, he is said to have ordered it to be burned, and to have hardly yielded to the request of Augustus that it might be left to the judgment and revision of his friends, Tucca and Varius He was buried, by his own desire, near Naples; where, at the erest of the rock that over- hangs the grotto of Posilipo,* beneath a low ivy-grown roof of stone, the traveller may still read his modest epitaph :-
